81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     DB2Flex, and ORAFlex 3.x
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-20 by Aaron Gulack
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOCK_TABLE {FileName} {FileName1} {FileName2} {FileName3}...
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  FileName            The name of file to be locked. Can be more than one
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_CHECK_TABLE
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Use this command to verify that a given table exists on the
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL backend. This command takes three arguments, a string containing the
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// name of the database, a string containing the name of the user and finally
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a string containing the name of the table being checked. If the table exists,
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the program proceeds normally. If the table does not exist then the flag
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// "finderr" is set to true. Note that in order to handle the error a check must
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// be done on the "finderr" variable.
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions All three parameters are less than 256 characters long.
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-20 by Aaron Gulack
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_CHECK_TABLE {database} {username} {table}
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  database            Name of the database
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  username            Name of the user
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  table                       Name of the table being checked
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CHECK_TABLE "testDB" "user" "Customer"
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (finderr) Begin
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln "This table does not exist"
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command allows you to put an additional constraint on
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// your finds, moving filtering to the SQL backend. Using this command can
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// result in significantly improved performance, since the server network traffic
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// reduced. Note that the SQL statement passed for this command is added onto
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the predefined Database SQL statement so treat it as such. Because of this,
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// it will almost always begin with "AND" followed by the desired constraint.
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions Parameter may be more than 255 characters long so redirect to method.
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-20 by Aaron Gulack
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SQL_CONSTRAINT GET_SQL_CONSTRAINT DF_FIELD_PROGRAMMATIC_DEFAULT
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT of {file} to {variable}
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  file                        Name or Number of the file.
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  variable            A SQL expression that constrains the data
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT of 1 to (SFormat('AND "%1"."%2" = ' + "'%3'", "Customer", "Status", "Active"))
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For_All Customer by Index.1 do
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End_For_All
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81451>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT Global Integer iFunction String sConstraint
81453>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver MertechInc_FileNumber MertechInc_DriverName Function iFunction CALLBACK 0 PASSING sConstraint MertechInc_Blank 0 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81458>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
81459>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81459>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT_PROGRAMMATIC Global Integer iFunction
81461>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver MertechInc_FileNumber MertechInc_DriverName Function iFunction CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank 4 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81466>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_SQL_CONSTRAINT
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the current SQL constraint for the given
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// table.  If there is no current constraint, then a blank string is returned.
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions Parameter may be more than 255 characters long so redirect to method.
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-20 by Aaron Gulack
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SQL_CONSTRAINT SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_SQL_CONSTRAINT of {File} to {variable}
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  File                        Name or number of the file
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  variable            The string containing the constraining SQL expression
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sCon
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT of Customer to (SFormat('AND "%1"."%2" = ' + "'%3'", "Customer", "Status", "Active"))
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_SQL_CONSTRAINT of Customer to sCon
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For_All Customer by Index.1 do
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sCon
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End_For_All
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81467>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_GET_SQL_CONSTRAINT Global Integer iFunction Returns String
81469>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sConstraint
81469>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String 0 to sConstraint
81470>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81470>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver MertechInc_FileNumber MertechInc_DriverName Function iFunction CALLBACK 0 PASSING sConstraint MertechInc_Blank 3 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81475>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sConstraint
81476>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_CONSTRAINT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to toggle on or off the current SQL
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// constraint that is set for a table. To deactivate the current constraint,
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// pass the constant DEACTIVATE to this command. to reactivate the constraint,
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// pass ACTIVATE to this command.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-20 by Aaron Gulack
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT GET_SQL_CONSTRAINT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_CONSTRAINT of {File} to {Activate|Deactivate}
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  File                        Name or Number of the file
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  Activate            Activates the constraint
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  Deactivate          Deactivates the constraint
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_SQL_CONSTRAINT of Customer to (SFormat('AND "%1"."%2" = ' + "'%3'", "Customer", "FirstName", "Aaron"))
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CONSTRAINT of Customer to Deactivate
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For_All Customer by Index.1 do
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End_For_All
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CREATE_TD_FILE
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description A .TD file is created when the attribute is set to True.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-20 by Aaron Gulack
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CREATE_TD_FILE {variable}
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  variable            True to create the .TD file, false doesn't create it.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        OPEN_INT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to replace the OPEN command in DataFlex.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// It can be useful when accessing tables that are not in the current filelist.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// To access these tables, the INT and FD files must be in the directory. From
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// there, all that is needed is to open the table using this command under an
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// alias name. If the command is executed successfully then the table can be
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// queried normally as if it were a standard table. Note that if the desired
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// table is already in the filelist or doesn't have an INT file then this
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command will act as a normal open command.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-21 by Aaron Gulack
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax OPEN_INT {variable} as {aliasName}
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  variable            The name of the int file without the extension.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  aliasName           The alias name being used to query this table.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// OPEN_INT "customer" as Customer
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For_All Customer by Index.1 do
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End_For_All
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_OPEN_MODE
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to enable an option known as "Lazy Open
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Mode". When turned on the table's metadata i.e. table, columns, index
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// descriptions, is deferred until a field is accessed, even if a OPEN has
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// already been done. This can significantly improve an application's initial
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// performance, especially when a large number of files are opened when the
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// program is launched. By default, tables are set to open normally, but by
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// passing the constant LAZY_MODE to this command, it can be altered to use
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// this mode. Note that when this mode is activated, it effects all tables
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// that are opened. To deactivate this feature, pass the constant "DEFAULT"
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to this command at any time. This is the preferred method to activate or
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// deactive this feature but it can also be set globally in the .INI file.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Default Value: DEFAULT (Off)
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-21 by Aaron Gulack
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_OPEN_MODE to {DEFAULT/LAZY_MODE}
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  DEFAULT                     Used to turn of the lazy mode feature.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  LAZY_MODE           Turns on the lazy mode feature
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_OPEN_MODE TO LAZY_MODE
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open "customer.int" as Customer
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ...
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ...
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find gt Customer by Index.1
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_STMT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Use this command to set an SQL statement to be executed on the
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// desired table. The string passed to this command must be a valid SQL
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// expression and must be on a table that has already been opened. Note that
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// when using this command, the SQL_PREPARE_STMT and SQL_EXECUTE_STMT must be
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// used in addition to carry out the expression. The option to pass the file
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// name as an extra parameter is used in cases where the data needs to be
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// fetched directly into the record buffer of the specified file.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions Parameter may be more than 255 characters long so redirect to method.
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-21 by Aaron Gulack
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_APPEND_STMT SQL_PREPARE_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SET_STMT [of {file}] to {variable}
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         Name or number of the file (optional)
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     String containing the SQL statement
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_SET_STMT of Customer to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sID sFirstName sLastName sDOB
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (Found)
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sFirstName sLastName sDOB
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sID
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sFirstName
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sLastName
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sDOB
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81477>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_SET_STMT Global String sStatment
81479>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver MertechInc_FileNumber MertechInc_DriverName Function 22 CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank sStatment 0 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81484>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_APPEND_STMT
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to append a command string to the
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command buffer initialized by SQL_SET_STMT. SQL_APPEND_STMT was added
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// so that long SQL expressions could be broken into smaller strings and
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// appended to a dynamic command buffer, which is then passed to the server.
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// The SQL_APPEND_STMT will concatenate a string to the command buffer
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// initialized by the SQL_SET_STMT command. SQL_APPEND_STMT can be called as
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// many times as necessary to complete the SQL expression. Subsequently, the
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT command executes the completed command.  The option to
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// pass the file name as an extra parameter is used in cases where the data
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// needs to be fetched directly into the record buffer of the specified file.
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions Parameter may be more than 255 characters long so redirect to method.
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-22 by Aaron Gulack
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_STMT SQL_PREPARE_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_APPEND_STMT [of {file}] to {variable}
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         The name or number of the file (optional)
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     The string to be appended to the current SQL expression
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_APPEND_STMT to " CUSTOMER.PHONE_NUMBER, CUSTOMER.FAX_NUMBER"
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_APPEND_STMT of Customer to " CUSTOMER.PHONE_NUMBER, CUSTOMER.FAX_NUMBER"
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sID sFirstName sLastName sDOB
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (Found)
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sFirstName sLastName sDOB
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sID
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sFirstName
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sLastName
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sDOB
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81485>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_APPEND_STMT Global String sStatement
81487>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver MertechInc_FileNumber MertechInc_DriverName Function 22 CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank sStatement 1 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81492>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        APPEND_UPDATE_COLUMN
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Append a given string to the existing SQL statement
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// already set.
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions Parameter may be more than 255 characters long so redirect to method
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-23 by Aaron Gulack
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax APPEND_UPDCOL_STMT {variable} for {fileName}.{fieldName} {fields...}
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                             SQL expression to be appended
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param fileName                             Name of the file
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param fieldName                    Name of the field
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param fields...                    Any additional fields, use the file.field format
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81493>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_APPEND_UPDATE_COLUMN Global String sStatement
81495>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver MertechInc_FileNumber MertechInc_DriverName Function 22 CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank sStatement 1 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81500>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_APPEND_UPDCOL_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Used to optimize the update process of columns being loaded
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// with the same value.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-23 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_APPEND_UPDCOL_STMT [of {file}] Value {variable} for {fileName}.{fieldName} {fields...}
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         The name or number of the file (optional)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     The value being uploaded
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param fileName                     The name of the file
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param fieldName            The name of the field
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param fields...            Any additional fields, use the file.field format
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT    of Customer to "UPDATE CUSTOMER SET"
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_APPEND_STMT of Customer to " ASC11='x', ASC12='y', ASC13='z'"
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_APPEND_UPDCOL_STMT of Customer value 0 ;
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     for Customer.ID Customer.Purchases Customer.Credit ;
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_APPEND_STMT of Customer to " WHERE RECNUM=1"
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_CURSOR_TYPE
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Specify the SQL cursor type to be used during the next
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// embedded SQL statement execution.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-23 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SET_CURSOR_TYPE to {TYPE_NONE/TYPE_CLIENT/TYPE_SERVER}
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param TYPE_NONE                    the default cursor type should be used
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param TYPE_CLIENT                  a client side cursor should be used
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param TYPE_SERVER                  a server side cursor should be used
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CLEAR_INT_CACHE
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Clears all memory-cached INT info. This is used in the
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// test framework to force a "reload" of int info which the framework
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// modifies for its tests. This is a different cache than the TD files
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// which are a file based cache of the structure for use at file open.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-23 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CLEAR_INT_CACHE
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CREATE_INVERSE_KEY_FUNCTIONS
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Create SQL Functions to handle Inverse Key columns.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All (v10.1 and above)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-23 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CREATE_INVERSE_KEY_FUNCTIONS
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Prepares a statement and opens a cursor to be executed by
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT. This command tells the server to parse the SQL statement
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// created by the respective SQL_SET_STMT and all subsequent SQL_APPEND_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// statements and to allocate cursor handles to be used to fetch the data.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// A cursor can be thought of as a pointer to a record set. The CURSOR_TYPE
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// argument is only supported by SQLFlex and by default SQLFLex is using a
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// TYPE_SERVER cursor type to all embedded SQL. TYPE_CLIENT should be used only
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// for the statements that are querying LOB columns i.e. TEXT, NVARCHAR(MAX),
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// VARCHAR(MAX), IMAGE, VARBINARY(MAX), XML. If the cursor type is
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// TYPE_SERVER and a LOB type column is selected, MS SQL Server will not be
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// able to get into a transaction, either explicitly or implicitly through a
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// REREAD, LOCK, SAVERECORD, etc.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-23 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_STMT SQL_APPEND_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_PREPARE_STMT [of {file}] CURSOR_TYPE {TYPE_NONE/TYPE_CLIENT/TYPE_SERVER}
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         The name or number of the file (optional)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param CURSOR_TYPE          Used if the cursor type is being set, do not include otherwise
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param TYPE_NONE            Default cursor will be used
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param TYPE_CLIENT          A client side cursor should be used
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param TYPE_SERVER          A server side cursor should be used (Default)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_PREPARE_STMT of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_PREPARE_STMT CURSOR_TYPE TYPE_SERVER
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_PREPARE_STMT of Customer CURSOR_TYPE TYPE_CLIENT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sID sFirstName
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sFirstName
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_BIND_COLUMN
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Clears all cached INT info. This should be merged with
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT, but has to remain as a separate command for
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// compatibility.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-26 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_BIND_COLUMN FileNumber FieldNumber | DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The number of the file
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber                  The number of the field
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to fetch the returned data of a
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// specified SQL expression into the given field in the record buffer. By
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// passing any number of fields to this command, the fetched record will then
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// be put into the subsequent fields in the record buffer. The order of the
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// fields must be the same as the order of the columns being retrieved from
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the SQL expression. SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW can then be called to take the data
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// retrieved from the server and place it into the corresponding fields in the
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// buffer. Instead of specifying each field, DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS can be passed,
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// which will retrieve every column in the table.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-26 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_STMT SQL_APPEND_STMT SQL_PREPARE_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT of {file} to {field/DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS}
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                 Name or number of the file
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param field                        Name or number of the field (can be multiple)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS  Used instead of the field to retrieve all columns in the file
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT of Customer to DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (Found)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.ID
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.LastName
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.DOB
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute the SQL expression created
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// by the SQL_SET_STMT and any subsequent SQL_APPEND_STMT commands issued
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// after a SQL_PREPARE_STMT. If the results will be sent to the record
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// buffer directly, then the file must be specified. An optional parameter
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// can also be passed, indicating the maximum number of rows to be sent to
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the local cache. This is done by adding the constant ROWCOUNT followed
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// by the maximun number.
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-26 by Aaron Gulack
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_STMT SQL_APPEND_STMT SQL_PREPARE_STMT SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_EXECUTE_STMT [of {file} ROWCOUNT {variable}]
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         Name or number of the file (optional)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Maximum number of rows to send to the local cache (optional)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer ROWCOUNT 10
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT of Customer to DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (Found)
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW of Customer
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.ID
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.LastName
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.DOB
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//This alias may be redundant. Is was only called from MertechInc_SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//which has been recoded to directly call SQL_EXECUTE_STMT - I.S. 2009-09-19
81501>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_PROCEDURE_EXECUTE Global
81503>>>>>>>>>>>>>    SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81518>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Transactions in SQL are used to maintain atomicity within
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// an process. If one procedure in the transaction fails, then they all
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// will fail. This command is used to start an SQL transaction. Inside of
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a transaction, there can be any number of SQL statements, none of which
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// will be executed until SQL_COMMIT_STMT is called. Note that transactions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// are generally only needed when a table is being altered.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-26 by Aaron Gulack
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SQL_COMMIT_STMT SQL_ROLLBACK_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "UPDATE CUSTOMER SET STATUS = 'Inactive'"
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_COMMIT_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_COMMIT_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Just as the SQL_EXECUTE_STMT is used to execute the SQL
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// statement in the block, this command is used to commit the transaction
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// started by SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT. When this command is called, any
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// preceding statements or procedures that are apart of the transaction will
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// be committed. If one or more of these statements fail, then none of them
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// will be successful, thus maintaining atomicity.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-27 by Aaron Gulack
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT SQL_ROLLBACK_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_COMMIT_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "UPDATE CUSTOMER SET STATUS = 'Inactive'"
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_COMMIT_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_ROLLBACK_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Rolls back an SQL transaction, any data changes inside the
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// transaction will not be committed by the server.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-27 by Aaron Gulack
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT SQL_COMMIT_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_ROLLBACK_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_START_TRANSACTION_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "DELETE FROM CUSTOMER WHERE ID = 2145"
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Err) Begin
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///             SQL_ERROR_MESSAGE errorString
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln errorString
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_ROLLBACK_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Else
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln "SQL Statement successful - committing"
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_COMMIT_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_TRANSACTIONS_ALLOWED
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to toggle on or off the ability to
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// complete transaction to the server. Passing false to this command will
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// not allow transactions to be made, passing true will allow the transactions.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-27 by Aaron Gulack
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_TRANSACTIONS_ALLOWED of {server} to {variable}
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                               The name of the server being used
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Boolean to enable or disable transactions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_TRANSACTIONS_ALLOWED of "localhost" to True
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to fetch the next row returned by the
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// associated SQL statement. The SQL statement is created from the
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT and executed with the SQL_EXECUTE_STMT. This command can be
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// used in two ways. If the results are to be attached to variables, then no
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// file needs to be specified, just the variables for each column in the row.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If the results are to be inserted into the record buffer directly, then the
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// file must be specified. From there, a SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT can be used to
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// bind the fetched row to the specific fields in the file. Note that the
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// columns are fecthed in the order that the SQL statement generates them, so
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the variables must follow the same order. The two constants, "found" and
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// "finderr" are set depending on whether the next row was found.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-27 by Aaron Gulack
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_STMT SQL_APPEND_STMT SQL_PREPARE_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW [of {file}] into {variable}
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  file                                The name or number of the file
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param  variable                    The variable that the next column in the fetched row will be put into (can be multiple)
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW of Customer
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sRecnum sID
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sID sRecnum
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER ID"
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_APPEND_STMT to " BY NAME DESC"
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (found)
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sRecnum sID
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     If (found) Begin
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///             Showln sID
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    End
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT of Customer to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT of Customer
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT of Customer to DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (Found)
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW of Customer
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.ID
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///             Showln Customer.LastName
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_RESULT_SET
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Fetches the next row in the result set returned by a
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// query or stored procedure.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-27 by Aaron Gulack
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_RESULT_SET into {variable}
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     The variable receiving the result (can be multiple)
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get a chunk of data from a column
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// retrieved through an embedded SQL statement. By passing the column number
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and the offset number, the chunk will be put into the specified variable.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// To specify how big of a chunk to get, use the SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE command.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Otherwise the maximum length will be retrieved. An optional variable can
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// also be passed which will store the length of the chunk. Note that unlike
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// LOB_READ, this command works for any column type, not just LOB columns.
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_GET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_SET_MAX_DATA_SIZE SQL_GET_MAX_DATA_SIZE
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK COLUMN {column} OFFSET {offset} to {variable} {length}
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param column                               Column number to get chunk from
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param offset                       Offset to start at for the chunk
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned chunk
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Variable to hold the chunk length
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sBio
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE to 150
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK COLUMN 6 OFFSET 1 to sChunk iLength
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sChunk
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln iLength
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81519>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK Global Integer iColumn Integer iOffset Returns String
81521>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local Integer iChuck_Size
81521>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sChunk
81521>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81521>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //Get current Chuck size and pre size string
81521>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_CHUNK_SIZE CALLBACK 0 PASSING iChuck_Size MertechInc_Blank 1 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81526>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String iChuck_Size to sChunk
81527>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81527>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //Get data
81527>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_GET_DATA_CHUNK CALLBACK 0 PASSING iColumn sChunk iOffset RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81532>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81532>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //sArg1 (iColumn) contains the number of bytes returned, so move it to
81532>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //MertechInc_Arg1 to pass the value back
81532>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Move iColumn to MertechInc_sArg1
81533>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81533>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sChunk
81534>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the size of the chunk to retrieve when
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// using SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK. Whatever number is set here will be the
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// length of the chunk that is retrieved, as long as it does not exceed
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the maximum chunk size.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK SQL_GET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_SET_MAX_DATA_SIZE SQL_GET_MAX_DATA_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Length of chunk to retrive
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sBio
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE to 150
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK COLUMN 6 OFFSET 1 to sChunk iLength
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sChunk
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln iLength
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_CHUNK_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command gets the size of the chunk being retrieved
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// from SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK and puts it into the specified variable.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK SQL_SET_MAX_DATA_SIZE SQL_GET_MAX_DATA_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_CHUNK_SIZE to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the chunk size
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_CHUNK_SIZE to iLength
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_MAX_DATA_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the maximum size for data chunks
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// retrieved through SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK. If SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE is higher
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// than the maximum size set with this command, then this will override
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// it and the chunk will be no longer than the maximum size set here.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_GET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK SQL_GET_MAX_DATA_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SET_MAX_DATA_SIZE to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Max length to allow for chunks
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_MAX_DATA_SIZE to 1000
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_MAX_DATA_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the maximum chunk size allowed
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// for SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_GET_CHUNK_SIZE SQL_GET_DATA_CHUNK SQL_SET_MAX_DATA_SIZE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_MAX_DATA_SIZE to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the maximum chunk size
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_MAX_DATA_SIZE to iLength
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_NUM_COLS
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the number of columns retrieved
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// from an SQL expression result set. Since the column number is based on
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the result set, this command cannot be used when the results are being
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// bound to the record buffer.  If this command is used with the record
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// buffer or if no columns are found, -1 is returned.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-28 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_PREPARE_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_SET_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_NUM_COLS to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the number of columns.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE FIRSTNAME = 'Aaron'"
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_RESULT_SET_NUM_COLS to iNumCols
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln iNumCols
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_RESULT_SET_NUM_COLS
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Returns the number of columns in the result set.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-28 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_NUM_COLS
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_RESULT_SET_NUM_COLS to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the number of columns
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Integer iNumCols
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE FIRSTNAME = 'Aaron'"
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_RESULT_SET_NUM_COLS to iNumCols
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln iNumCols
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_NUM_ROWS
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the number of rows retrieved
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// from a result set of an SQL expression. It cannot be used when binding
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the result set to the record buffer.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Note: The number of rows may not always be available, depending
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// on server and cursor types.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-30 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_PREPARE_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_NUM_ROWS to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the number of rows
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Integer iNumRows
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_NUM_ROWS to iNumRows
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln iNumRows
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_COL_NAME
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to retrieve the name of a specified
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// column within an SQL result set. An optional second variable can be used
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to retrieve the size of the specified column. Note that this command
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// cannot be used when the results are being directly binded to the record
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// buffer, it can only be used for the results of an SQL statement.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-30 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_NUM_COLS
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_COL_NAME {columnNumber} to {variable} [{length}]
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param columnNumber                 The column number being used
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                             String variable for the column name
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Variable to hold the column length (optional)
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sColumnName
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Integer iLength
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active'"
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_COL_NAME 1 to sColumnName iLength
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// showln sColumnName
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// showln iLength
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_RESULT_SET_COL_NAME
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Returns the column name being populated from the result set.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-30 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_COL_NAME
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_RESULT_SET_COL_NAME {columnNumber} to {variable} [{length}]
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param columnNumber                 The column number being used
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                             String variable for the column name
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Variable receiving the column length (optional)
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_COL_ATTRIBUTE
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get specific column information from
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the columns in a result set of an SQL statement. By passing one of the
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// supported attributes below, the command will return the desired information.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Note that some attributes only work with specific drivers. See the list
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// below for more information.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Supported attributes are:
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dl>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>SIZE        </dt><dd>The maximum length of the column</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>DATA_LENGTH </dt><dd>Length of data currently in the column</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>DECIMALS    </dt><dd>If numeric, shows number of decimal places</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>LABEL       </dt><dd>Returns the column name in ORAFlex and MySQLFlex</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>COLUMN_NAME </dt><dd>Returns the name of the column</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>TABLE_NAME  </dt><dd>Returns the name of the table (MySQLFlex only)</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>SQLTYPE     </dt><dd>Returns the number representing the SQL data type</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>NULLABLE    </dt><dd>Returns true if null is allowed, false otherwise (doesn't work in PostgreSQL)</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// <dt>DFTYPE      </dt><dd>Dataflex type column is mapped to</dd>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// </dl>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_COL_ATTRIBUTE of {columnNumber} {attribute} to {variable}
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param columnNumber                 The number of the column that is being examined
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param attribute                    The attribute being checked (see list)
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                             Variable to hold the attribute value
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sFirstName sLastName sColumn1Name sColumn2Name
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sFirstName sLastName
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_GET_COL_ATTRIBUTE of 1 COLUMN_NAME to sColumn1Name
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_GET_COL_ATTRIBUTE of 2 COLUMN_NAME to sColumn2Name
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln (sColumn1Name + " = " + sFirstName)
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln (sColumn2Name + " = " + sLastName)
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DDO_GET_BIND_RSPARAMETERS
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Recursively calls DO_GET_BIND_RSPARAMETERS.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-30 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_GET_BIND_RSPARAMETERS
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Gets bound parameters values for result set call.
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-08-30 by Aaron Gulack
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81535>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_DO_GET_BIND_RSPARAMETERS Global Integer bSQLFlex String sArg1 String sArg2 Integer iArg Returns String
81537>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sReturnValue
81537>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local Integer iSize
81537>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81537>>>>>>>>>>>>>    move 0 to iSize
81538>>>>>>>>>>>>>        SQL_GET_COL_ATTRIBUTE of iArg DATA_LENGTH to iSize
81555>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81555>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81555>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String (iSize+1) to sReturnValue
81556>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Move (|CI$10000 * iArg) To iArg // Shift column number 16 bits to the left
81557>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function 24 CALLBACK 0 PASSING sReturnValue MertechInc_Blank iArg RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81562>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81562>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sReturnValue
81563>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_NEXT_RESULT_SET
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used when working with SQL statements that
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// return multiple result sets. In that scenario, calling this command will
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// move to the next result set. That set can now be fetched or binded to
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// columns on a table.
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-02 by Aaron Gulack
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_NEXT_RESULT_SET [of {file}]
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                 Name or number of the file (optional)
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SP_HELP CUSTOMER"
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sTable sOwner sTableType dtCreated
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sTable
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sOwner
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sTableType
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln dtCreated
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_NEXT_RESULT_SET
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sColumnName sColumnType sComputed sLength
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sColumnName
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sColumnType
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sComputed
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sLength
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DDO_PASS_ARGUMENTS
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Calls DO_PASS_ARGUMENTS until the argument is "BINDING" and
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// then stops.
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_PASS_ARGUMENTS
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Builds parameter statements for stored procedures and adds
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// them to the current query.
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      internal
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DDO_BIND_PARAMETERS
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Recursively calls DO_BIND_PARAMETERS until the keyword
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// "BINDING" is encountered.
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_BIND_PARAMETERS
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Binds parameters for a stored procedure call.
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81564>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_DO_BIND_PARAMETERS Global String sValue String sName Integer iLength
81566>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_BIND_PARAMETER CALLBACK 0 PASSING sValue sName iLength RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81571>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_BIND_PAR_RET
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Binds parameters for a stored procedure call.
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DDO_GET_BIND_PARAMETERS
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Recursively calls DO_GET_BIND_PARAMETERS.
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_GET_BIND_PARAMETERS
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Gets bound parameter values for a stored procedure call.
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81572>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_DO_GET_BIND_PARAMETERS Global Integer bSQLFlex String sArg1 String sArg2 Integer iArg Returns String
81574>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sReturnValue
81574>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local Integer iSize
81574>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81574>>>>>>>>>>>>>    if (MertechInc_DriverName = SQLFLEX) ;                move (iArg+1) to iArg
81577>>>>>>>>>>>>>//        SQL_GET_COL_ATTRIBUTE of iArg DATA_LENGTH to iSize
81577>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81577>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String (iSize+1) to sReturnValue
81578>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function 24 CALLBACK 0 PASSING sReturnValue MertechInc_Blank iArg RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81583>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81583>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sReturnValue
81584>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_OUTPUT_VALUE
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the value of a specific
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// parameter associated with a stored procedure.  Although this
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command will work with any parameter, it is mostly used with
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// IN/OUT or OUT parameters as their value will more often be important
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// once returned. When multiple values are returned, this command can be
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// more efficient than other options. Note that the specified parameter
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// must first be defined using the SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER command
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// in order to work properly.
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_GET_OUTPUT_VALUE {parameter} to {variable}
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param parameter            Number of the parameter
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the parameter's value
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_NAME "user.getCustomerStatus" NUMPAR 1
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER 1 to sCustomerID IN_OUT
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PROCEDURE_EXECUTE
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_OUTPUT_VALUE 1 to sStatus
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_NAME "user.getCustomerStatus" NUMPAR 2
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER 1 to sCustomerID IN
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER 2 to sStatus OUT
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PROCEDURE_EXECUTE
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_OUTPUT_VALUE 2 to sStatus
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>// OLI:
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>// This function is identical in operation to SQL_GET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER, so just do a replace
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_FETCH_COLUMN
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to retrieve a specified column from a
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// result set of an SQL statement. Note that this command cannot be used to
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// replace SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW but is used in addition to it when only one
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// column is needed. For most cases, SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW can be used alone
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to retrieve the columns desired so this should only be used if there is
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a specific reason to do so.
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-05 by Aaron Gulack
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_FETCH_COLUMN {columnNumber} into {variable}
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param columnNumber    Number of the column to fetch
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable        Variable to hold the fetched value
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_NUM_COLS to iCols
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For fieldIndex from 1 to iCols
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_FETCH_COLUMN fieldIndex into sValue
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sValue
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81585>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_FETCH_COLUMN Global String sArg1 String sArg2 Integer iArg Returns String
81587>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sReturnValue
81587>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local Integer iSize
81587>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81587>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Move 0 to iSize
81588>>>>>>>>>>>>>        SQL_GET_COL_ATTRIBUTE of iArg DATA_LENGTH to iSize
81605>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81605>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81605>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String (iSize+1) to sReturnValue
81606>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Move (|CI$10000 * iArg) to iArg // Shift column number 16 bits to the left
81607>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function 24 CALLBACK 0 PASSING sReturnValue MertechInc_Blank iArg RESULT MertechInc_iRet
81612>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81612>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sReturnValue
81613>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_SCHEMA_NAME
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set the schema name to be used when
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// opening tables. Note that this command will override the schema name that
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// is set in the INT file.  The default schema for the current user is used
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// when no name is set.
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex and ORAFlex
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-24 by Aaron Gulack
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_SCHEMA_NAME
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_SCHEMA_NAME to {schema}
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Name of the schema
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_SCHEMA_NAME to 'CustomerSchema'
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// OPEN "CUSTOMER.INT" as CUSTOMER
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_SCHEMA_NAME to 'SalesSchema'
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// OPEN "SALESP.INT" as SALESP
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_SCHEMA_NAME
81614>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the name of the schema being
