82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to call a stored procedure on the SQL
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// backend. To successfully call a procedure with this command, a string
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// must be passed containing a valid procedure name. In addition, if the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// procedure takes any arguments, they must also be passed using the constant
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// "passing" along with all of the needed arguments. If the procedure has a
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// return value, then SQL_GET_FUNCTION_RETURN or SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW can be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// used to get the value(s). If an error is found then the indicator "Err"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// is set to true.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-09-25 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE {procedure} Passing {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param procedure            Full name of the procedure
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Argument being passed (can be multiple)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE "sys.sp_addmessage" passing 50003 15 "Please enter a valid date"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_SQLSERVER_PROCEDURE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to call a stored procedure on the SQL
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// backend. To successfully call a procedure with this command, a string
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// must be passed containing a valid procedure name. In addition, if the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// procedure takes any arguments, they must also be passed using the constant
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// "passing" along with all of the needed arguments. If the procedure has a
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// return value, then SQL_GET_FUNCTION_RETURN, SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW or
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_PROCEDURE_RETURN can be used to get the value(s). If an error is found
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// then the indicator "Err" is set to true.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_SQLSERVER_PROCEDURE {procedure} Passing {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param procedure            Full name of the procedure
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Argument to be passed (can be multiple)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CALL_SQLSERVER_PROCEDURE "sys.sp_addmessage" passing 50003 15 "Please enter a valid date"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        END_CALL_PROCEDURE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to close any open cursors created
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// by the respective stored procedure. Cursors are used in MSSQL to make
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the results from one procedure temporarily available to other procedures
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// or triggers. To avoid causing unwanted results, it is good practice to
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// use this command once a procedure call is completed.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax END_CALL_PROCEDURE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE "sys.sp_spaceused" Passing "Customer"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_PROCEDURE_RETURN to sValue
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// END_CALL_PROCEDURE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sValue
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_PROCEDURE_RETURN
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get a returned value from a stored
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// procedure using MSSQL. Note that this command can only handle one
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// returned value and must be used after the procedure has already been
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// built and executed.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_PROCEDURE_RETURN to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the returned value
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_NAME "sys.sp_spaceused" NUMPAR 1
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER 1 to "Customer" IN
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PROCEDURE_EXECUTE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_PROCEDURE_RETURN to sSpaceUsed
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sSpaceUsed
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_MIRROR_SERVER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to programmatically set the mirror
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// server for the database. This is to be used along with SQl server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// failover mirroring. Note that this simply sets the server and database
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to be used for mirroring. All set up for the servers must already be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// working properly through SQL Server.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions A compatible version of SQL Server is being used
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex v9.2 and above
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_MIRROR_SERVER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_MIRROR_SERVER to {server} {database}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       The name of the mirror server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     The database acting as a mirror
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_MIRROR_SERVER to "(localdb)\v11.0" "MirrorDB"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_MIRROR_SERVER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the name of the server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and database being used for failover mirroring. Mirroring must
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// be properly set up in SQL Server for this command to return the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// correct values.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex v9.2 and above
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_MIRROR_SERVER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_MIRROR_SERVER to {server} {database}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Variable to hold the name of the mirrored server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Variable to hold the name of the mirrored database
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_MIRROR_SERVER to sServer sDatabase
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        COPY_DATA
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to copy data from a DAT file to an
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL table. Both the source and the destination files are opened, the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// data is copied and then the files are closed. This is usually used
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// along with CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE, which creates the structure
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and then this command will insert the data. If needed, this command
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// can also work backwards, copying data from an SQL table to a DAT file.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to using the Flex2SQL Migration Tool and can
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// improve performance when used in the right situations. Note that in
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// order for this process to work properly the table being copied can not
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// be opened. Because of this, a manual login must take place, using
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// something like LOGIN_SQLFLEX or LOGIN. Since this only copies the data,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE can be used to create the table structure.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Because COPY_DATA requires no user interaction, an optional callback
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// function can be passed for tracing purposes. By passing the constant
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// "CALLBACK" followed by the object name, a function can be used to set
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// up messages for tracking and error handling. Below is more information
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// regarding this callback object.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This function should follow this pattern:
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Function Callback String sText Integer iStatusID Returns Integer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// sText - Message corresponding to the current status ID
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// iStatusID - Integer value mapping to the current status constant:
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                     DF_MESSAGE_PROGRESS_TITLE    Sent when SQLFlex starts the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                                              process
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///             DF_MESSAGE_HEADING_1         Sent when SQLFlex is about to
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                                              copy the source data
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///             DF_MESSAGE_ERROR             Sent when an error occurs
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///             DF_MESSAGE_PROGRESS_STATUS   Sent each time an additional
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                                              10% of the data is copied
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Returning false each time the function is called will continue
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// copying process. Returning true will end it.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Another optional parameter that can be used is a constrain on the data
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// being copied. This is done by passing the constant "CONSTRAIN" followed
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// by an SQL constrain statement. When passing a constrain but not a callback
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// object, pass 0 for the callback before passsing the constrain.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE CONVERT_DAT_FILE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax COPY_DATA {from} to {destination} [CALLBACK {function}] [CONSTRAIN {variable}]
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param from                         Table to copy from.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param destination          Table to copy to.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param function             Object with callback function (optional)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     SQL contraint to use when copying (optional)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Object CallBackObj is a Array
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Function Callback String sText Integer iLogicalID Returns Integer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///         If (iLogicalID = DF_MESSAGE_ERROR) Begin
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///             Showln "Error"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                             Showln sText
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                             Function_Return True
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///         End
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///         Else Showln sText
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                     Function_Return False
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     End_Function
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End_Object
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pass123" "sql_drv"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE Customer.File_Number "Customer"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// COPY_DATA "Customer" to "sql_drv:Customer" CALLBACK (Callback(Self)) CONSTRAIN "STATUS = 'Active'"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        ORAFlex_REVISION
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will put the current version (decimals included)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// of the Oracle driver associated with the current workspace into the specified
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// variable.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DRIVER_REVISION
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax ORAFlex_REVISION {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     String variable to hold the returned version
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ORAFlex_REVISION sVersion
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        KEEP_FILES_OPEN
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Keep the files, currently in use, open after the server is
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// logged out. Sometimes an application needs to login to the same server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// with a different user id. When logging out, however, the drivers
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// automatically close all opened files. The overhead of opening these files
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// should be avoided if the user will work with the same files that were
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// closed. KEEP_FILES_OPEN keeps all files opened after a user logs out
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// from the server.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax KEEP_FILES_OPEN of {server}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server               Name of the server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Set the maximum number of cursors you want the driver to use.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// The driver will recycle the least used cursors if this limit is hit.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// The trade off is between increased resources on the server and
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// re-preparing of cursors.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For a program that keeps 40+ files opened at the same time, 255 is a good
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// number for the open cursors parameter. For programs that open less than
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// 40 files, any number between 100-255 is sufficient. These numbers can be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// changed based on available server resources.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// On Oracle this value should not exceed the value of open_cursors in
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// init.ora
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Note: Only change this setting if you are having performance issues
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and the server is indicating you are using up too many cursors or too
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// much memory. GET_OPENED_CURSORS can be used to check the number of
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// cursors the server has opened. If this number is hitting the limit,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// it is worth increasing the number, as long as the server has enough
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// resources.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS GET_OPENED_CURSORS
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS of {server} to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       The name of the server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Maximum number of cursors
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will return the maximum number of open
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// cursors allowed by the server.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS GET_OPENED_CURSORS
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS of {server} to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the maximum number of open cursors
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_OPENED_CURSORS
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the number of cursors currently
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// open on the server.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS of {server} to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the number of cursors currently open
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        ACTIVATE_TIME_STAMP
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will specify whether or not to show the time
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// portion of a date field. When set to ON, the time portion will be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// included, OFF will just show the date. This is the same as changing
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the date format with "ALTER SESSION SET nls_timestamp_format". Note that
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// this will only take effect if the date is put into a string variable.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax ACTIVATE_TIME_STAMP of {server} to {ON/OFF}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ACTIVATE_TIME_STAMP of "localhost/orcl.localdomain" to OFF
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to 'SELECT * from USER."Customer" '
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sFirstName sLastName sDOB
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sDOB
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_ORACLE_STORED_FUNCTION
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute a function stored in Oracle.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to building a function with the SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER and SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE commands. This command
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// builds and executes the function by setting the full function name, the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// parameter(s) to pass and the variable to hold the returned value. Note that
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// this command can only return a single value so SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME must be used when dealing with multiple return
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// values.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFLex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_FUNCTION
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_ORACLE_STORED_FUNCTION {function} Returns {variable} Passing {argument}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param function                     Full name of the function
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CALL_ORACLE_STORED_FUNCTION "user.getCustomerStatus" Returns sStatus passing sCustomerID
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_PGSQL_STORED_FUNCTION
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute a function stored in Oracle.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to building a function with the SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER and SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE commands. This command
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// builds and executes the function by setting the full function name, the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// parameter(s) to pass and the variable to hold the returned value. Note that
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// this command can only return a single value so SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME must be used when dealing with multiple return
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// values.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     PGFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_FUNCTION
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_PGSQL_STORED_FUNCTION {function} Returns {variable} Passing {argument}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param function                     Full name of the function
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CALL_PGSQL_STORED_FUNCTION "user.getCustomerStatus" Returns sStatus passing sCustomerID
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        MERTECH_LANGUAGE_SUPPORT
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Sets the support language for the driver.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFLex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax MERTECH_LANGUAGE_SUPPORT of {server} to {language}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server               The name of the server being used
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param language             The language to set support to
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to initialize a SAVE_BUFFER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// statement. Doing this will allow a specified set of records to be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// stored in the buffer before a save takes place. Once the buffer is
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// filled, it will be saved automatically. This set of commands can be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// used to efficiently save a large number of records. Once the buffer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// is full, the save occurs automatically and the buffer will be emptied
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// out. It is good practice to use this method inside of a transaction to
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// maintain atomicity. Note that these commands should not be used in
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// conjuction with finds.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END SQL_SAVE_BUFFER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of {FileName} to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Number of records to store in the buffer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of Transactions to 10
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For i from 0 to 1000
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Move i to Transactions.ID
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of Transactions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of Customer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_BUFFER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to send a record to the "Save
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Record" buffer. It must be used along with SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END. SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN sets the number of
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// records to store in the buffer before a save is done on all the records
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// at once. Each time a record is created, this command should be called
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to insert it into the buffer. Using this set of commands can be useful
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to efficiently save a large number of records. Once the buffer is full,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the save occurs automatically and the buffer will be emptied out. It is
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// good practice to use this method inside of a transaction to maintain
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// atomicity.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of {FileName}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of Transactions to 10
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For i from 0 to 1000
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Move i to Transactions.ID
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of Transactions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of Customer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command indicates the end of the extended record
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// buffer and forces a save of any data currently in the buffer.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See         SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN SQL_SAVE_BUFFER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of {FileName}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of Transactions to 10
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For i from 0 to 1000
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Move i to Transactions.ID
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of Transactions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of Customer
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_SET_ATTRIBUTES
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Unknown - Not in help - Not call by any other macros
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-08-18 By Ian Smith
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        ENABLE_TRACE_ON
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command enables driver level tracing to the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// specified file. Enabling trace on an application and using it
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// in conjunction with SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE is a good way to study
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// particular problems you encounter in the driver. SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// allows you to insert sections of your code into the trace file.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This command can also set the trace to three different levels,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// allowing different amounts of information to be logged. Note that
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// trace files can become very large so it is good practice to only
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// turn them on when specifically needed.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 DISABLE_TRACE_ON SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax ENABLE_TRACE_ON to {fileName} Debug_Level [{constant}]
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param fileName                     The path of the file to send the trace to
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param constant             DETAIL_LEVEL1, DETAIL_LEVEL2, DETAIL_LEVEL3 (optional)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example ENABLE_TRACE_ON TO "C:\Temp\trace_file.txt" Debug_Level DETAIL_LEVEL3
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DISABLE_TRACE_ON
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command disables the current trace taking
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// place on a driver.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See ENABLE_TRACE_ON SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax DISABLE_TRACE_ON
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to create a SQL table from a .DAT
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// file. The table being copied must be not be opened in order for this
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command to work properly. This is the programmatic equivalent to
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// using the Flex2SQL Migration Tool. Optional restructuring options
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// can be specified here (see below) as well as an alternative table
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// name than the physical name of the .DAT file. Note that this only
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// creates the  table structure, no data will be copied here. To copy
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the data, use COPY_DATA after the table has been created.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK         - Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME      - Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL - forces all fields to be created as NOT NULL.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 COPY_DATA CONVERT_DAT_FILE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE {FileNumber} [{options} {table}]
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber           Number of the file
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param options                      DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL (optional)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param table            name of table to use instead of physical name (optional)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pass123" "sql_drv"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE Customer.File_Number "Customer"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// COPY_DATA "Customer" to "sql_drv:Customer" CALLBACK (Callback(Self)) CONSTRAIN "STATUS = 'Active'"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CONVERT_DAT_FILE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is the programmatic equivalent to the
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Flex2SQL Migration Tool. With this command, a SQL table can be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// created from a .DAT table. This combines the COPY_DATA and
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE, creating the table structure and
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// copying all the data into the new table with one command. The
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// table being converted cannot be opened and so a manual login is
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// needed. Note that to specify the database to copy the table to,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// use SET_DATABASE_NAME. Below is a list of the optional restructure
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// options to use when creating the table.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK         - Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME      - Deprecated
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL - forces all fields to be created as NOT NULL.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE COPY_DATA
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CONVERT_DAT_FILE {FileNumber} [{options} {table}]
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber           Number of the file
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param options                      DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL (optional)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param table            Name of table to use instead of physical name (optional)
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pass123" "sql_drv"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CONVERT_DAT_FILE Customer.File_Number DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL "Customer"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set the file casing standard when
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// creating or restructuring tables. By default, all table and column names
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// are created using the specified casing. Passing FILE_CASING_UPPER or
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_LOWER will allow the names to be saved in uppercase or
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// lowercase respectively. This can be useful for backwards compatibility
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// where casing was important. Note that the casing standard for a file can
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// also be changed through mertech.ini. Below is a description of the constants
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// that can be passed to this command.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_UPPER : All created or edited object names will be converted to uppercase.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_LOWER : All created or edited object names will be converted to lowercase.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_KEEP (default) : All created or edited object names will maintain their inputed casing.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING to {constant}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     FILE_CASING_UPPER, FILE_CASING_LOWER, FILE_CASING_KEEP
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING to FILE_CASING_UPPER
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the file casing standard used
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// when creating or restructuring tables. Note that an integer is returned,
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// mapping to a casing method. Below are the meanings of the possible
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// returned integers.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// 0 - FILE_CASING_UPPER : All created or edited object names will be converted to uppercase.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// 1 - FILE_CASING_LOWER : All created or edited object names will be converted to lowercase.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// 2 - FILE_CASING_KEEP : All created or edited object names will maintain their inputed casing.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned casing
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING TO iCasing
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the default table space to use when
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// creating tables through Dataflex. A tablespace is a container of
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// segments (objects that have an allotted amount of space), i.e. tables
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and indexes.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex, PgFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Name of the default table space
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to "Users"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the default table space name for
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the current database.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex, PgFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the default table space name.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to sTableSpace
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the default table space for indexes
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// when creating tables through the DataFlex API. A tablespace is a
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// container of segments (objects that have an allotted amount of space),
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// i.e. tables and indexes.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex, PgFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09-2013 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the default index table space name.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE to "Users"
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the default table space name for
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// indexes in the current database.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex, PgFlex
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE to {variable}
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the default index table space name.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE to sTableSpace
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        ENABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Scripting is used for testing and preparation. This
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command allows structural changes to be compiled and tested without
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// actually making any of the changes. Any table restructuring done
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// between this command and DISABLE_SCRIPTING will not actually be
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// committed but will instead create a mock INT file. The script and
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// INT file can then be retrieved and examined for testing purposes.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 DISABLE_SCRIPTING GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK GET_INT_CHUNK
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax ENABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ENABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     //Table restructuring would go here
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK OFFSET 0 to sChunk sLength
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sChunk
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command ends any scripting started by ENABLE_SCRIPTING.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// The mock INT file and script can then be retrieved and examined.
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2010-12-13 By Marcelo Nachbar
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING  GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK GET_INT_CHUNK
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ENABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     //Table restructuring would go here
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK OFFSET 0 to sChunk sLength
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sChunk
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82408>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_GET_RESTRUCTURE_SCRIPT Global Integer iLong Integer iOffset Returns String
82410>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local Integer iChuck_Size
82410>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sChunk
82410>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82410>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //Get current Chuck size and pre size string
82410>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_CHUNK_SIZE CALLBACK 0 PASSING iChuck_Size MertechInc_Blank 1 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82415>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String iChuck_Size to sChunk
82416>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82416>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //Get data
82416>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_RESTRUCTURE_SCRIPT CALLBACK 0 PASSING sChunk iOffset iLong RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82421>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82421>>>>>>>>>>>>>    // Replace insert a CR before any LF character
82421>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Move (Replaces(Character(10), sChunk, Character(13)+Character(10))) to sChunk
82422>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82422>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sChunk
82423>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns a chunk of the script generated
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// from the restructuring done inside of ENABLE_SCRIPTING and
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DISABLE_SCRIPTING. Since some scripts can be very large, the script
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// can be looped through, grabbing chunks at a time.
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING GET_INT_CHUNK
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK OFFSET {offset} to {variable} [{length}]
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param offset                       Specifies the offset to start at for the chunk
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the chunk
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Length of chunk returned (optional)
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ENABLE_SCRIPTING
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     //Table restructuring would go here
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK OFFSET 0 to sChunk sLength
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sChunk
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_INT_CHUNK
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns a chunk of the INT file generated
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// from the restructuring done inside of ENABLE_SCRIPTING and
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DISABLE_SCRIPTING. Since some INT files can be very large, the file
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// can be looped through, grabbing chunks at a time.
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING GET_SQL_SCRIPT_CHUNK
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_INT_CHUNK OFFSET {offset} to {variable} [{length}]
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param offset                       Specifies the offset to start at for the chunk
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the chunk
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Length of chunk returned (optional)
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ENABLE_SCRIPTING
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     //Table restructuring would go here
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_INT_CHUNK OFFSET 0 to sChunk sLength
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sChunk
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        REPORT_STMT
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is an alternative to DataFlex's "Report"
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command. This allows embedded SQL to be used to fetch data instead of
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// standard table queries.. All of the finds, for example, normally found
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// in "Report" are replaced by SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW.
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     n/a
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax See DataFlex / Visual DataFlex documentation
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// /Header
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// __/__/____                                                        Page ___.
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                 MERTECH DATA SYSTEMS, INC. - NOT FOR RESALE
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ID   NAME
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// /Body
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ____ _________________________
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// /Total
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Records printed = _______.
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// /*
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// OPEN SALESP
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// direct_output "con:"
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// // Write the complete SELECT statement to retrieve the expected records from your REPORT
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// // Must include the expression to qualify the required records and specify the order by as well
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// sql_set_stmt of salesp to "select recnum, id, name from SALESP where recnum > 5 order by id"
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// sql_prepare_stmt of salesp
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// sql_bindcolumns_stmt of salesp to salesp.recnum salesp.id salesp.name
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// sql_execute_stmt of salesp
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Report_stmt SALESP By Index.1
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Section Header
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Sysdate Header.1
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Move PageCount to Header.2
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     output header
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Section Body
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Print Salesp.id   to Body.1
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Print Salesp.name to Body.2
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     output body
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Section Total
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Return
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ReportEnd
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_SERVER_CFG
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command, when passed a valid server name, returns
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the a value for the specified attribute. See the list below for an
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// explanation of each attribute.
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SERVER_REVISION    Returns the major version, to the left of the decimal, of the server
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SUPPORT_DESC       Returns 1 if Server supports descending index segments
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SUPPORT_CASE       Returns 1 if Server supports case insensitive index segments
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SERVER_VERSION     Returns the full version of the server
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SERVER_ENCODING    Returns the Server Encoding
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CONNECTION_ACTIVE  Returns 1 if the connection to the server is active
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CITEXT_SUPPORT     Returns 1 if Server supports citext, a PostgreSQL data type
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_SERVER_CFG {constant} of {server} to {variable}
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     SERVER_REVISION,SERVER_MIN_REVISION,SUPPORT_DESC,SUPPORT_CASE,SERVER_VERSION,SERVER_ENCODING,CONNECTION_ACTIVE
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server being checked
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_SERVER_CFG SERVER_VERSION of "localhost" to sVersion
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82424>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_GET_SERVER_CFG Global String sServer Integer iAttribute Returns String
82426>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sReturnValue
82426>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82426>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String 512 to sReturnValue
82427>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82427>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_GET_SERVER_CFG CALLBACK 0 PASSING sServer sReturnValue iAttribute RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82432>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82432>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //If iAttribute = SERVER_VERSION or SERVER_ENCODING then return sReturnValue
82432>>>>>>>>>>>>>    //else we need to return MertechInc_iRet
82432>>>>>>>>>>>>>    If ((iAttribute = 4) or (iAttribute = 5)) Function_Return sReturnValue
82435>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Else                                      Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
82437>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_CONNECTION_STATUS
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Retrieve the connection status for the specified server.
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-25 By Ian Smith
82438>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
