82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DIRECT_PATH_LOAD
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_INITIALIZE_SEQUENCE
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to initialize all auto increment
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// columns, or sequences in Oracle, of the specified table to be the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// highest number plus one. This is useful when inserting a large amount
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// of records in the table and the sequence is not being updated because
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the auto incremented column is being manually filled.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex PgFlex
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_INITIALIZE_SEQUENCE of {FileNumber}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The file number
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_APPEND
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to append data to an existing LOB
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// column in the database. When called, the data corresponding field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// in the buffer is appended to the respective column in the database.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This can be very useful when saving data that exceeds VDF size limits
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// but falls within the limits of the SQL database. Note that this command
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// must write to a file that is active and locked. Also the save is handled
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// within the command so no extra calls are needed to save the changes made.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_LOB_ADD_CHUNK
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_APPEND of {FileName} {FieldNumber}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being appended to
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Direct_Input 'C:\Mertech.xml'
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Lock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_WRITE of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Repeat
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///        Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///        SQL_LOB_APPEND of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Until (SeqEOF)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Unlock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Close_Input
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer By Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_LENGTH
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the length of the data in the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// specified column. This command must be used after a proper FIND to
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// ensure that a valid record is in the buffer. This can be a useful
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command for checking if uploaded data exceeds size limits.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_LENGTH of {FileName} {FieldNumber} to {variable}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the length
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_READ
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command reads a chunk of data from a specified LOB
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// column, moving it into its corresponding field buffer. Because the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// chunk will be moved into the field buffer, it can only be as large as
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the buffer allows. To account for this, the constants FIRST or NEXT
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// are passed as well indicating whether to grab the first chunk for
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the buffer or the next. Each chunk grabbed will be as large as allowed.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// All these things considered, when reading data larger than the field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// buffer, it is good practice to perform the read in a loop, adding the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// length each time. Another optional parameter that can be passed is a
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// variable that will store the length of the chunk. Note that a LOB read
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// must be done after a successful find on the record.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_READ of {FileName} {FieldNumber} {FIRST/NEXT} [{length}]
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being read from
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FIRST                        Reads the first chunk of data
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param NEXT                         Reads the next chuck of data (if larger than buffer limit)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Variable to hold the chunk length (optional)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Direct_Output ('binary:Mertech.pdf')
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Gt customer by Index.1
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of customer 13 to liLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (liLength > 0)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Write customer.comments
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     SQL_LOB_READ of customer 13 Next liLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Close_Output
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_WRITE
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to write data to a LOB column.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// By passing the file name and field number of the LOB column, this
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command will take the current value of the respective field in
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the field buffer, write it to the database and save it. Any data
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// currently in that field will be overridden by the data from the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// buffer. Note that this command must write to a file that is active
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and locked. Also this command handles the save so no extra calls
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// are needed to save the changes.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_WRITE of {FileName} {FieldNumber}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being written to
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Direct_Input 'C:\Mertech.xml'
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Lock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_WRITE of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Repeat
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///        Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///        SQL_LOB_APPEND of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Until (SeqEOF)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Unlock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Close_Input
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer By Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_LOADFROMFILE
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command loads an external file into a specified LOB
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// column. After specifying the file name and field number, the path and
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// file must then be passed respectively. When using Oracle, instead of
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// passing the directory, a directory alias must be passed. This alias
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// can be created using a "CREATE DIRECTORY" statement in SQL. For more
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// information on setting this directory alias, see the Oracle help.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// For other servers, the file must be a local file available to the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// application that is calling the command. Note that this command must
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// write to a file that is active and locked. Also this command handles
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the save so no extra calls are needed to save the changes.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_ERASE LOB_TRUNCATE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_LOADFROMFILE of {FileName} {FieldNumber} From {path} {file}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB column being used
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param path                         The path of the file, excluding the file name
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         The name of the file, including the extension
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Lock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    LOB_TRUNCATE OF customel 13 to 0 // Customer.Comments
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    // Directory name is case sensitive.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    // Make sure the name case matches
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    LOB_LOADFROMFILE OF customel 13 FROM "C:\Mertech\FilesToLoad" "Mertech.XML"
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Unlock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_ERASE
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to erase a portion of data from a
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// LOB column. For text fields, the portion of data to be erased is
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// replaced with white space, and in binary fields, with 0X0. To erase
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a portion of the data, pass the length to erase as well as the number
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to offset from. For this command to work properly, it must be done
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// after a valid find. Note that the save is handled inside this command
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// so no extra commands are needed to save the changes.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_LOADFROMFILE LOB_ERASE LOB_TRUNCATE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_ERASE OF {FileName} {FieldNumber} {length} {offset}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB column being erased
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param Length                       Length of chunk to erase from column
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param offset                       Starting position for erase
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Gt customer by Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Lock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq customer by Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// LOB_LENGTH OF customer 13 to liTotalLength
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// LOB_ERASE  OF customer 13    liTotalLength 1
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Unlock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_TRUNCATE
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to trim a LOB column down to a
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// specified length. By passing the table name and column number, the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// value in the column can then be trimmed down the specified length.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This can be a useful command for clearing out a column before entering
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// new data into it. Note that this command must write to a file that is active
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and locked. Also this command handles the save so no extra calls
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// are needed to save the changes. This command can be used to clear out a field before adding new data
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_LOADFROMFILE LOB_ERASE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_TRUNCATE of {FileName} {FieldNumber} to {variable}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          The field number
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       New length to truncate to
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Lock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE of Customer 13 to 0 // Customer.Comments
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Unlock
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command currently serves no function.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER of {FileName}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_ENABLE_RECONNECT
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Allow MySql Driver to auto reconnect after a time-out.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Driver auto-reconnect feature handles the issue where MySQL
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// will kick off a user after inactivity.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQL
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-11 By Ian Smith
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_ENABLE_RECONNECT of <ServerName> to dftrue/dffalse
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param ServerName  Server Name.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Usage SQL_ENABLE_RECONNECT Of sServerID To dftrue
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to call a stored procedure on the SQL
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// backend. To successfully call a procedure with this command, a string
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// must be passed containing a valid procedure name. In addition, if the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// procedure takes any arguments, they must also be passed using the constant
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// "passing" along with all of the needed arguments. If the procedure has a
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// return value, then SQL_GET_FUNCTION_RETURN or SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW can be
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// used to get the value(s). If an error is found then the indicator "Err"
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// is set to true.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE {procedure} Passing {argument}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param procedure            Full name of the procedure
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE "getCustomerStatus" passing sCustomerID sStatus
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER 2 to sStatus
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute a function stored in MySQL.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to building a function with the SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME,
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER and SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE commands. This command
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// builds and executes the function by setting the full function name, the
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// parameter(s) to pass and the variable to hold the returned value. Note that
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// this command can only return a single value so SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME must be used when dealing with multiple return
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// values.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_FUNCTION
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION {function} Returns {variable} Passing {argument}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param function                     Full name of the function
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION "getCustomerStatus" Returns sStatus passing sCustomerID
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_SET_ALL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Sets the parameters for a MySQL stored function call.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax DO_SET_ALL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS [sParam1 [sParam2 . sParamn]]
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param sParam1.n    Parameters for the stored function
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the number of available MSSQL
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// servers detected in the network. When used with GET_SQLSERVER_NAME,
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// all the available server names can be easily retrieved.
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions SQL Server Browser Service is started and firewall is configured properly
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_SQLSERVER_NAME
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to {variable}
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold number of servers
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to iServers
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (i <= iServers)
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     GET_SQLSERVER_NAME i to sServer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sServer
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Increment i
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82469>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVERS Global Returns Integer
82471>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 SQLFLEX Function CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER_COUNT RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82476>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82476>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
82477>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_SQLSERVER_NAME
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the name of the server based on the
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// specified index number. The number of servers can be retrieved from
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS and the names can be indexed from that
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// number.
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions SQL Server Browser Service is started and firewall is configured properly
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVER_NAME {index} to {variable}
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param index                The numbered index name to retrieve
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the server name
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to iServers
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// While (i <= iServers)
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     GET_SQLSERVER_NAME i to sServer
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Showln sServer
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>///     Increment i
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Loop
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82478>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVER_NAME Global Integer iIndex Returns String
82480>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sName
82480>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82480>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String 80 to sName
82481>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 SQLFLEX Function CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER CALLBACK 0 PASSING sName iIndex CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER_SERVER RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82486>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82486>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sName
82487>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Turn on / off Row_Count for specified server.
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION OF <Server> To <State>
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param Server      Name of server to turn On / Off Row_Count
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param State       TRUE = turn on Row_Count  FALSE = turn off Row_Count
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Comment This SHOULD ALWAYS BE TURNED ON
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82488>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS Global String sServer Integer iState
82490>>>>>>>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
82492>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82492>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS CALLBACK 0 PASSING sServer iState CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82497>>>>>>>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR True
82500>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//IGS - commented out by a.n. Other
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//#REPLACE UseRowCountInTransactions SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Gets the Row_Count setting for specified server.
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION OF <Server> To <State>
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param Server      Name of server to get Row_Count state of
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param State       Variable to hold returned value
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82501>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS Global String sServer Returns Integer
82503>>>>>>>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
82505>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82505>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS CALLBACK 0 PASSING sServer MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82510>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82510>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
82511>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command controls the date format of data returned
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// through embedded SQL. If set to DATAFLEX, then the dates will be
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// returned in whatever format is set in DF_DATE_FORMAT. When set to
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// NATIVE, this command will force dates to return dates in the format
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// specified on the SQL server. Note that in order for the variables to
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// be in the right form, they need to be string variables.
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT to {DATAFLEX/NATIVE}
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT to NATIVE
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82512>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_USE_DATAFLEX_DATEFORMAT Global Integer iState
82514>>>>>>>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
82516>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82516>>>>>>>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_DriverName eq SQLFlex Begin
82518>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_DFLEX_DATE_FORMAT CALLBACK 0 PASSING iState MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82523>>>>>>>>>>>>>        IF MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR TRUE
82526>>>>>>>>>>>>>    End
82526>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82526>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
82527>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82527>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function SQL_USE_DATAFLEX_DATEFORMAT Global Returns Integer
82529>>>>>>>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
82531>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82531>>>>>>>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_DriverName eq SQLFlex Begin
82533>>>>>>>>>>>>>        CALL_DRIVER 0 MertechInc_DriverName FUNCTION CALLDRV_USE_DFLEX_DATE_FORMAT CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82538>>>>>>>>>>>>>    End
82538>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82538>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Else Move DFFALSE to MertechInc_iRet
82540>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82540>>>>>>>>>>>>>    function_return MertechInc_iRet
82541>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify how to handle blank
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and zero values on the SQL backend. Since blank or zero values can
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// often be stored as null in the server database, this command allows
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// that to be altered if needed. When set to true, a value will be
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// inserted into blank records to keep them from being null. See the
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// list below for what value will be stored instead of null. If set to
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// false, values will be stored normally in the database. Note that this
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command effects all data types.
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_ASCII and DF_TEXT -              ' ' (one blank space)
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_BCD -                                    0 (zero)
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_DATe and DF_DATETIME -   00/00/0000 for MYSQL
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/0001 for Oracle MSSQL, and Postgre
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/1753 for MSSQL Datetimes
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_BINARY -                                 0X0
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIELDS_NULL GET_FIELDS_NULL
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL to {variable}
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Boolean variable to indicate how to handle null values
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82542>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL Global Integer iState
82544>>>>>>>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
82546>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82546>>>>>>>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
82548>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING iState MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82553>>>>>>>>>>>>>        If MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR True
82556>>>>>>>>>>>>>    End
82556>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82556>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure
82557>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82557>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82557>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82557>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82557>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function SQL_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL Global Returns Integer
82559>>>>>>>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
82561>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82561>>>>>>>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
82563>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82568>>>>>>>>>>>>>    End
82568>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82568>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Else Move DFFALSE to MertechInc_iRet
82570>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82570>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
82571>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIELDS_NULL
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify how to store blank or zero
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// values in the database. Since database can sometimes store these value,
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// i.e. '' or 0, as null, using this command can be useful in managing that.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// When set to true, any value in a column of the given type considered blank
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// or 0 will be stored as null in the database. Setting it to false will cause
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the server to save as it normally would. Note that this command is used to
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// set specific data types only, it can not effect all types at once. Below is
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a list of value that would be considered blank/zero values.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_ASCII and DF_TEXT -              ' ' (one blank space)
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_BCD -                                    0 (zero)
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_DATe and DF_DATETIME -   00/00/0000 for MYSQL
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/0001 for Oracle MSSQL, and Postgre
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/1753 for MSSQL Datetimes
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_BINARY -                                 0X0
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_FIELDS_NULL SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIELDS_NULL {datatype} to {variable}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param datatype                     DF_ASCII, DF_BCD, or DF_DATE
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Boolean to indicate how to handle blank data
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_FIELDS_NULL
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will return the value of SET_FIELDS_NULL for
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the specified data type.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIELDS_NULL SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_FIELDS_NULL {datatype} to {variable}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param datatype                     DF_ASCII, DF_BCD, or DF_DATE
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the value of SET_FIELDS_NULL
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used when scripting structural changes.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// It is the same as using ENABLE_SCRIPTING and Structure_Start separately.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// It allows structural changes to be compiled and tested without
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// actually making any of the changes. Any table restructuring done
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// between this command and STRUCTURE_END_DYNAMIC will not actually be
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// committed but will instead create a mock INT file. The script and
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// INT file can then be retrieved and examined for testing purposes.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC of {FileNumber}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The number of the file
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        STRUCTURE_END_DYNAMIC
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command ends the scripting started by
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC. It is the same as calling Structure_End
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and DISABLE_SCRIPTING separately.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC of {FileNumber}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The number of the file
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description Attachs an MS SQL mdf to the current server instance. If
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the passed database is already attached, no error is generated.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// The SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB command is intended for use with our new support
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// of Microsoft LocalDB's.  When using LocalDB's a common use case might be
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to attach to a customer DB, do some work on it, and then detach this DB
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// and attach to a different DB.  This was possible using stored procedures,
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// but the code had some complexities that a developer need not worry about.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// When you attach a database, you must pass the database name, along with
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the path to an MDF file which contains the database.  Any associated LDF's
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// (log files) and NDF's (secondary data files) must be in the same folder.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If you call SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB on a database that is already attached,
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// no error will be generated.  After you call SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB, you
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// should call SET_DATABASE_NAME if you wish to make the attached database
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the currently selected database.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB will work on all supported version of SQL server.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB {database} on {filePath}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param filePath                     Path of the MDF file
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB "MTSample" ON "C:\Mertech\Data\SampleDb.mdf"
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description The SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB command is intended for use with our
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// new support of Microsoft LocalDB's.  When using LocalDB's a common use
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// case might be to attach to a customer DB, do some work on it, and then
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// detach this DB and attach to a different DB.  This was possible using
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// stored procedures, but the code had some complexities that a developer
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// need not worry about.  A detach can only be done if the database passed
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// has no open connections.  As part of the detach process, the command
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// closes ALL open files (even those not associated with this database or
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// driver).
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// NOTE: SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB will often fail to execute if you are testing
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// your application from the studio.  This is because the studio itself
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// normally has open connections to the database.  If you test your
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// application outside of the studio and the studio is closed (and any
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// other application or tools that access this database are closed) you
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// can successfully detach the database.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB {database}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB "TestDB"
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to a
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// fixed value. This can be useful because doing a SELECT COUNT(*) is
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a very expensive process to the server. Many applications do counts
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// often and using this command can help cut down the server traffic.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Sometimes when counts are used, an exact number is not necessary so
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a fixed value, updated occasionally can be used. By setting this
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command to 0 or greater, the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED will be
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// set to that specified value and the internal SELECT COUNT(*) will be
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// suppressed. If this command is set to something less that zero,
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED will be dynamically calculated whenever it is
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// called.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// The default value for this command is -1
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status              Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to {variable}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Fixed value for DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to 10000
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// if it has been set to a fixed value by SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If anything greater than or equal to 0 is returned then that is the
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// fixed value returned by any SELECT COUNT(*) statements, internal or
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// not. If something less than zero is returned, then DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// returns a dynamic count whenever it is called.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// By default the value of this is -1
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status              Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_FILE_RECORDS_USED to {variable}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the fixed value
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to iRecords
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// a fixed value of zero. That way anytime a SELECT COUNT(*) is done,
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// zero is returned, cutting down on server traffic. This is the same
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// as setting SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to 0.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command resets the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// -1. That way anytime a SELECT COUNT(*) is done, it returns the actual
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// count of records. This is the same as setting SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to -1.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>// Private:
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>// Get the filenumber of a file.field parameter
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>// Private:
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>// Get the fieldnumber of a file.field parameter
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>// Minimum required DataFlex version for new LOB support below is VDF 4
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>TYPE tMertechLOB_Args
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize       AS WORD          // always the size of the structure (verification + versioning)
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nField       AS DWORD         // always the field number
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.pszData      AS POINTER
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nSize        AS DWORD
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nOffset      AS POINTER
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>END_TYPE
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_LOB
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command replaces whatever is currently in a LOB Field
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// with the data passed. It writes to a client side buffer. It can be used
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// to Write an arbitrary amount of data into a LOB.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If passed an empty String, it will remove all the contents of the LOB.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If you wish to Set a LOB back to NULL, please use the SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// command.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Unlike the previous call LOB_WRITE, this call does not
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// perform the Save. This must be done separately.
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_SET_LOB {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                The name of the file containing the LOB field
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName               The name of the LOB field being set
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                The variable to use to set the field's value
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sLine
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Direct_Input "C:\bigFile.xml"
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to ""
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Read_Block sLine 262144
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to sLine
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       While (not(SeqEof))
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///          Read_Block sLine 262144
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///          SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sLine
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Loop
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Unlock
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Close_Input
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82572>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField String sData
#REM AMBIGUOUS METHODS ON .DESKTOP. ARE .NOT. RECOMMENDED (OBSOLETE TECHNIQUE)
82574>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args       // can drop local command if minimum vdf version is 6
82574>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82574>>>>>>>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
82575>>>>>>>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
82575>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
82576>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
82577>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put (AddressOf(sData))    to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
82578>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put (length(sData))       to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
82579>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82579>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_WRITE CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82584>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Procedure // MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to add additional chunks to the buffer
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// before saving the record. After SQL_SET_LOB has been called
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK can be called as many times as needed to add additional
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// chunks of data before a save. It can also be called independent of
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_LOB to append data to an existing LOB column.
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Unlike the previous call LOB_APPEND, this call does not perform
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the save. This must be done separately.
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                The name of the file containing the LOB field
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName               The name of the LOB field being set
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                The variable to add as the LOB chunk
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sLine
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Direct_Input "C:\bigFile.xml"
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to ""
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Read_Block sLine 262144
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to sLine
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       While (not(SeqEof))
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///          Read_Block sLine 262144
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///          SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sLine
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Loop
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Unlock
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Close_Input
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82585>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField String sData
#REM AMBIGUOUS METHODS ON .DESKTOP. ARE .NOT. RECOMMENDED (OBSOLETE TECHNIQUE)
82587>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
82587>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82587>>>>>>>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
82588>>>>>>>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
82588>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
82589>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
82590>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put (AddressOf(sData))    to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
82591>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put (length(sData))       to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
82592>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82592>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_APPEND CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82597>>>>>>>>>>>>>end_procedure // MertechInc_SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used for getting the value of a specified LOB
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// field. Two optional parameters can be passed specifying the offset and
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// length of the chunk to get. Passing these parameters essentially makes this
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// call the same as SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK.
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Depending on the situation, the two calls can be interchanged for improved
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// code readability. Excluding these additional parameters will get the whole
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// field value within DataFlex variable size limits.
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax     SQL_GET_LOB {FileName.FieldName} TO {variable} [ OFFSET {offset} LENGTH {length} ]
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file that contains the specified LOB field
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the LOB field
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the LOB value
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              offset                          Integer amount to offset when getting the LOB value (optional)
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              length                          Length of value to get from the LOB field (optional)
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sResult
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Move 262144 to iChunkSize
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Move 0      to iChunk
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Direct_Output ('Binary:' + sDestFileName)
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Write sResult
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Loop
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Close_Output
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82598>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField Integer iOffset Integer iLength Returns String
#REM AMBIGUOUS METHODS ON .DESKTOP. ARE .NOT. RECOMMENDED (OBSOLETE TECHNIQUE)
82600>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
82600>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sData
82600>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local DWord  nSize
82600>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82600>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Move "" To sData
82601>>>>>>>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
82602>>>>>>>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
82602>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
82603>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
82604>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82604>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_GET_LENGTH CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82609>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82609>>>>>>>>>>>>>    GetBuff from sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize to nSize
82610>>>>>>>>>>>>>    If nSize GT 0 Begin
82612>>>>>>>>>>>>>      If (iOffset=0 and iLength=0) Begin
82614>>>>>>>>>>>>>        ZeroString nSize to sData
82615>>>>>>>>>>>>>            //Send Assert (AddressOf(sData) <> 0) ("AddressOf(sData) is NULL") DFTrue
82615>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Put (AddressOf(sData)) to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
82616>>>>>>>>>>>>>      End
82616>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82616>>>>>>>>>>>>>      Else Begin
82617>>>>>>>>>>>>>        ZeroString iLength to sData
82618>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Put (AddressOf(sData)) to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
82619>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Put iLength            to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
82620>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Put iOffset            to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nOffset
82621>>>>>>>>>>>>>      End
82621>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82621>>>>>>>>>>>>>      Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_READ CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82626>>>>>>>>>>>>>    End
82626>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82626>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Else Begin
82627>>>>>>>>>>>>>        Move "" to sData
82628>>>>>>>>>>>>>    End
82628>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82628>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return sData
82629>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function // MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used for getting a chunk of data from a specified
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// LOB field. The difference between this command and SQL_GET_LOB is only that
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// the parameters OFFSET and LENGTH are not optional when using this command.
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// You may consider using this command to retrieve small portions of a very
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// large BLOB so as to reduce memory usage.
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax     SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK {FileName.FieldName} TO {variable} OFFSET {offset} LENGTH {length}
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file that contains the specified LOB field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the LOB field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the LOB chunk
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              offset                          Integer amount to offset when getting the LOB chunk
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              length                          Length of chunk to get from the LOB field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sResult
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Move 262144 to iChunkSize
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Move 0      to iChunk
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       // Do something with the LOB data
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Loop
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the length of a specified LOB field.
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// It is useful, for example, in determining the number of iterations to
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// perform while reading from a LOB field using chunking.
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file containing the LOB field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the specified LOB field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the length of the field
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// String sResult
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Move 16384 to iChunkSize
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Move 0     to iChunk
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       // Do something with the LOB data
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Loop
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82630>>>>>>>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField Returns Integer
#REM AMBIGUOUS METHODS ON .DESKTOP. ARE .NOT. RECOMMENDED (OBSOLETE TECHNIQUE)
82632>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
82632>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local DWord  nSize
82632>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82632>>>>>>>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
82633>>>>>>>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
82633>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
82634>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
82635>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82635>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_GET_LENGTH CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
82640>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82640>>>>>>>>>>>>>    GetBuff from sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize to nSize
82641>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Function_Return nSize
82642>>>>>>>>>>>>>End_Function // MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set a LOB column to null. Often
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// LOB columns should either contain data or be null. A "blank" LOB column
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// often doesn't appear empty in other environments, so settings it back to
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// null is best.
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_SET_LOB_NULL    {FileName.FieldName}
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file containing the LOB field
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the specified LOB field
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>///
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// @Example
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>////
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Move iID to Customer.ID
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>///        SQL_SET_LOB_NULL Customer.Comments
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>///        Saverecord Customer
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>///    Unlock
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>/// End
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82643>>>>>>>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB_NULL String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField
#REM AMBIGUOUS METHODS ON .DESKTOP. ARE .NOT. RECOMMENDED (OBSOLETE TECHNIQUE)
82645>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
82645>>>>>>>>>>>>>
82645>>>>>>>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
82646>>>>>>>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
82646>>>>>>>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
